    <text>
        <body>
            <head>63. Telegram From the <orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">Department of
                    State</orgName> to the Embassy in <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd"
                    >Algeria</placeName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d63fn1">Source: Carter Library,
                    National Security Affairs, Staff Material, Middle East, Subject File, Box 1,
                    Algeria: 1–12/78. Secret; Priority; <gloss target="#t_Exdis_1">Exdis</gloss>.
                    Sent for information to Rabat, Nouakchott, Paris, Madrid, <gloss
                        target="#t_USUN_1">USUN</gloss>, Havana, <placeName
                        corresp="recNjfV4BLbp8Hnlq">Kinshasa</placeName>, Mogadiscio, and Addis
                    Ababa. Printed from a copy that was received in the White House Situation Room.
                    Drafted by <persName corresp="recoJB3QsHSMqYcVi">Bishop</persName>; cleared by
                        <persName corresp="reck3Idcn5DKa2Vdf">Houghton</persName> and in <gloss
                        target="#t_AF_1">AF</gloss>/I and P; approved by <persName
                        corresp="recwoY153LTKW4SoC">Saunders</persName>. (National Archives, RG 59,
                    Central Foreign Policy File, D780254–0757)</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1978-06-18T16:05:00+00:00">June 18, 1978, 1605Z</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>155012. Subj: <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Secretary</persName>’s June 10
                Meeting With <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName> Foreign
                Minister <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName>. Ref: <orgName
                    corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">State</orgName> 135959.<note n="2" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d63fn2">In telegram 135959 to Algiers, May 27, the <orgName
                        corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">Department</orgName> reported on <persName
                        corresp="recwoY153LTKW4SoC">Saunders</persName>’s May 25 meeting with
                        <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName>. (National
                    Archives, RG 59, Central Foreign Policy File, D780225–0036)</note>
            </p>
            <p>1. Summary: During a lengthy conversation <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd"
                    >Algerian</placeName> Foreign Minister <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt"
                    >Bouteflika</persName> gave <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu"
                    >Secretary</persName> a letter from President <persName
                    corresp="recFHGSIQJfkdnNvO">Boumediene</persName> to President <persName
                    corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8">Carter</persName> protesting <placeName
                    corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO">France</placeName>’s military intervention in the
                    <placeName corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK">Western Saharan</placeName>
                    conflict.<note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d63fn3">A copy of <persName
                        corresp="recFHGSIQJfkdnNvO">Boumediene</persName>’s May 20 letter to
                        <persName corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8">Carter</persName> is in the Carter
                    Library, National Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, President’s
                    Correspondence with Foreign Leaders File, Box 1, Algeria: President Houari
                    Boumediene, 5/77–6/78. See also <ref target="#d229">Document 229</ref>.</note>
                <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName> elaborated on this theme
                in discussion, criticizing the <placeName corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO"
                    >French</placeName> also for their military role in <placeName
                    corresp="recfpFrNXC2mjKxLP">Zaire</placeName> and <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName>. When he sought assurance there had
                been no change in <rs type="event" corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv">administration</rs>’s
                African policy, <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Secretary</persName> reminded
                him that U.S. has sought peaceful resolution of African disputes, while <placeName
                    corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviets</placeName> have fueled the fires of
                conflict with massive arms shipments. <gloss target="#t_FonMin_1">FonMin</gloss>
                said he had told <persName corresp="recDY3Qj3ewYuDRni">Castro</persName>, <persName
                    corresp="rec97wetyoXAfBn07">Kosygin</persName>, and <persName
                    corresp="rec2pzR5IgvBboOwH">Mengistu</persName> the <placeName
                    corresp="recN9Eiz6DYwp5D1W">Eritrean</placeName> conflict will have to be
                settled politically, and that <persName corresp="recDY3Qj3ewYuDRni"
                    >Castro</persName> had told him <placeName corresp="recrGN6dqTH4MaGw0"
                    >Cuban</placeName> troops would not become involved. On <placeName
                    corresp="rec8OcfTNjljldVnD">Namibia</placeName>, <persName
                    corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName> said <placeName
                    corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> will support a solution
                acceptable to the <rs type="topic" corresp="recDREWMpqciYXWtD">Front Line
                    states</rs>. <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName>
                admitted there have been secret peace talks between Rabat and Algiers on the
                    <placeName corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK">Western Sahara</placeName> war. However,
                he indicated these have not been productive.</p>
            <p>
                <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Secretary</persName> pledged continuing U.S.
                neutrality. <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName> outlined
                terms of a possible settlement. On the <placeName corresp="recJAi0OpNdSuYev5">Middle
                    East</placeName>, <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName>
                was highly critical of <persName corresp="recIigdM8sR9uq1Ip">Sadat</persName> and
                argued that the <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviets</placeName> be given
                a larger role in the peace process. <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu"
                    >Secretary</persName> took the occasion to give him a briefing on our current
                    <placeName corresp="recJAi0OpNdSuYev5">Middle East</placeName> policy. End
                summary.</p>
            <p>2. <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName> called on <persName
                    corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Secretary</persName> June 10 following request for
                appointment from <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName>
                Embassy, which said <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName> had
                been instructed to seek meeting by <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd"
                    >Algerian</placeName> President <persName corresp="recFHGSIQJfkdnNvO"
                    >Boumediene</persName>. Talks which lasted two and half hours covered following
                topics:</p>
            <pb facs="0191" n="170" xml:id="pg_170"/>
            <p>3. U.S. African policy and the <placeName corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO"
                    >French</placeName>: As discussion began, <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt"
                    >Bouteflika</persName> handed <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu"
                    >Secretary</persName> letter from <persName corresp="recFHGSIQJfkdnNvO"
                    >Boumediene</persName> to President <persName corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8"
                    >Carter</persName> (text, which being cabled <gloss target="#t_septel_1"
                    >septel</gloss>, protests <placeName corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO"
                    >French</placeName> military intervention in <placeName
                    corresp="rech4Y08vWrfyBSYC">Africa</placeName>). <persName
                    corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName> quickly took up same theme,
                claiming African Anglophones and those other African nations maintaining “policy of
                national independence” join <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd"
                    >Algeria</placeName> in opposition to <placeName corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO"
                    >French</placeName> action. Commenting that <placeName
                    corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO">French</placeName> appear to be acting on behalf of
                the West, <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName> asked
                rhetorically why the West intervened to support defective, incompetent and corrupt
                leaders against their own peoples. Accusing <placeName corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO"
                    >French</placeName> of engaging in colonial conquest, he said Paris is seeking
                encircle <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> by extending its
                influence in surrounding states. He suggested that if <placeName
                    corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> forced to choose between
                suffering <placeName corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO">French</placeName> attacks and
                permitting <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviets</placeName> to establish
                bases, <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> would do latter.
                Noting that U.S. is associated with <placeName corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO"
                    >France</placeName> and <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl"
                    >Morocco</placeName> in <placeName corresp="reczwlhWVrjQQqvft">Shaba</placeName>
                operation, <gloss target="#t_FonMin_1">FonMin</gloss> asked if this represented a
                long term change in U.S. policy. He called on U.S. to urge <placeName
                    corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO">France</placeName> to act with greater restraint in
                    <placeName corresp="rech4Y08vWrfyBSYC">Africa</placeName>. He then attacked
                African intervention force proposed by <placeName corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO"
                    >France</placeName>.</p>
            <p>4. Replying, <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Secretary</persName> assured
                    <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName> there has been no
                change in African policies of <persName corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8"
                    >Carter</persName>
                <rs type="event" corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv">administration</rs>, reminding him that
                new administration had substantially increased economic assistance to <placeName
                    corresp="rech4Y08vWrfyBSYC">Africa</placeName>, had given clear support for
                African majority rule in <placeName corresp="rectj5ZFht5r3NFPH">Southern
                    Africa</placeName> and had sought peaceful resolution of problems, while
                    <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviets</placeName> and Cubans poured in
                arms which escalated conflict. With regard to <placeName corresp="recfpFrNXC2mjKxLP"
                    >Zaire</placeName>, U.S. respected <gloss target="#t_OAU_1">
                    <orgName corresp="reclJ1I8Ix3s26TFu">OAU</orgName>
                </gloss> principle of <rs type="topic" corresp="recAPhAIrM8XS4R2T">territorial
                    integrity</rs>. Danger to civilians arose from violation of international
                frontier. U.S. response to requests for assistance from <placeName
                    corresp="recfpFrNXC2mjKxLP">Zaire</placeName>, <placeName
                    corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO">France</placeName> and <placeName
                    corresp="recsMAoWbTPQ8P24I">Belgium</placeName> was motivated by humanitarian
                factors. He added parenthetically that U.S. action was a specific response to
                situation in <placeName corresp="reczwlhWVrjQQqvft">Shaba</placeName> and not within
                the context of proposals for an African peacekeeping force. U.S. realizes
                fundamental reforms are necessary in <placeName corresp="recfpFrNXC2mjKxLP"
                    >Zaire</placeName> and will seek these for the benefit of the country’s people.
                    <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Secretary</persName> again invited
                    <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName> to look at record of
                U.S. African policy over previous 18 months and assured <gloss target="#t_FonMin_1"
                    >FonMin</gloss> that U.S. wants <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd"
                    >Algeria</placeName> to continue to pursue its policy of national
                independence.</p>
            <p>5. <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName> said he was reassured
                by <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Secretary</persName>’s reaffirmation of <rs
                    type="event" corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv">administration</rs>’s African policy.
                He said <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> also supported
                principle of <rs type="topic" corresp="recAPhAIrM8XS4R2T">territorial integrity</rs>
                and had demonstrated it in <placeName corresp="recqpBPi294emCIYE">Congo</placeName>,
                    <placeName corresp="recjMbjbjwwyRY1bP">Biafra</placeName> and <placeName
                    corresp="recTaHDu8DL4OjK8b">Ethiopian</placeName> contexts. Mobutu’s accusations
                of <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName> complicity in renewed
                    <placeName corresp="reczwlhWVrjQQqvft">Shaba</placeName> incursion were prompted
                by <placeName corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO">French</placeName> and Moroccans, he
                claimed. He blamed South Africans for <placeName corresp="reczwlhWVrjQQqvft"
                    >Shaba</placeName> problem, indicating he thought they brought it on via their
                support for <persName corresp="recOg0D2c7q6UL8lj">Savimbi</persName> in an effort to
                distract attention from their designs in <placeName corresp="rec8OcfTNjljldVnD"
                    >Namibia</placeName> and <placeName corresp="recLDObMgYpHfaDfZ"
                    >Rhodesia</placeName>.</p>
            <p>6. <placeName corresp="rec8OcfTNjljldVnD">Namibia</placeName> and <placeName
                    corresp="recLDObMgYpHfaDfZ">Rhodesia</placeName>: As examples of U.S. efforts to
                promote peaceful settlements, <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu"
                    >Secretary</persName> outlined for <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt"
                    >Bouteflika</persName> current efforts <pb facs="0192" n="171" xml:id="pg_171"/>
                to reach agreement on future of <placeName corresp="reci2wP9wt5Z362ne"
                    >Zambia</placeName> and <placeName corresp="recLDObMgYpHfaDfZ"
                    >Rhodesia</placeName>. He expressed hope Algerians would use their good offices
                to get <gloss target="#t_SWAPO_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recRK1BVWO9mDe8eY">SWAPO</orgName>
                </gloss> to accept the principles formulated by the <orgName
                    corresp="recngRzMqHFSNhvvC">Group of Five</orgName>
                <note n="4" place="foot" xml:id="d63fn4">The <orgName corresp="recngRzMqHFSNhvvC"
                        >Group of Five</orgName>, comprised of <placeName
                        corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO">France</placeName>, the United States, the
                        <placeName corresp="rec3Gz23Bw0AZRDOQ">United Kingdom</placeName>,
                        <placeName corresp="recTdYKjeUHG9khQR">Canada</placeName>, and the
                        <placeName corresp="recf0aacz5ErR9cs4">Federal Republic of
                        Germany</placeName>, worked to resolve the conflict between the <orgName
                        corresp="recRK1BVWO9mDe8eY">South-West Africa People’s
                        Organization</orgName> (<placeName corresp="rec8OcfTNjljldVnD"
                        >Namibia</placeName>) and the South African Government.</note> which are
                supported by the <rs type="topic" corresp="recDREWMpqciYXWtD">Front Line
                states</rs>. He said U.S. also would appreciate any help Algerians could give to
                promote Rhodesian settlement.</p>
            <p>7. <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> fully supports F<rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recDREWMpqciYXWtD">ront Line states</rs>, <gloss
                    target="#t_FonMin_1">FonMin</gloss> said. Discussing Walvis Bay, <persName
                    corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName> expressed belief this issue is
                principal obstacle to <gloss target="#t_SWAPO_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recRK1BVWO9mDe8eY">SWAPO</orgName>
                </gloss>’s adhesion to <orgName corresp="recngRzMqHFSNhvvC">Group of
                Five</orgName>’s proposals. <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu"
                    >Secretary</persName> then outlined elements of public statement <orgName
                    corresp="recngRzMqHFSNhvvC">Group of Five</orgName> prepared to make concerning
                Walvis Bay if <gloss target="#t_SWAPO_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recRK1BVWO9mDe8eY">SWAPO</orgName>
                </gloss> would agree to defer resolution of its status until after elections. He
                also clarified other aspects of <orgName corresp="recngRzMqHFSNhvvC">Group of
                    Five</orgName> proposal and reactions of individual Front Line Presidents.
                Responding, <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName> described
                himself as personally reassured.</p>
            <p>8. <placeName corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK">Western Sahara</placeName>: Responding to
                    <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">the Secretary</persName>’s inquiry
                regarding press reports of talks between Rabat and Algiers, <persName
                    corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName> admitted these have occurred,
                asking <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Secretary</persName> to treat this
                information confidentially. He accused Moroccans of press leaks designed to
                forestall efforts by third parties to mediate dispute. If this behavior continued,
                he said, <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> will reveal that
                no progress has been made and that the two parties remain in total disagreement. His
                personal belief, <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName>
                claimed, is that Moroccans think <placeName corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO"
                    >French</placeName> intervened in <placeName corresp="rec8AtlHhYG0QfwTi"
                    >Mauritania</placeName> partially to prevent <placeName
                    corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName> from extending its borders to
                Nouakchott or even St. Louis. In brief discussion of possible solutions, <persName
                    corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName> said that realizing <persName
                    corresp="rec8m8MetQlvwXVeh">Hassan</persName> had put his throne at risk
                    <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> appreciates some
                concession must be made to his ambitions. He suggested <placeName
                    corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName> might keep portion of Sahara
                including <rs type="topic" corresp="reclnawDbQgAFDvnc">phosphate</rs> mines and part
                of seacoast, while Saharans received remainder of territory now occupied by
                    <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName> and <placeName
                    corresp="rec8AtlHhYG0QfwTi">Mauritania</placeName>. Although the Moroccan
                political parties are very bellicose, there are factions in <placeName
                    corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName> which favor peace, even within
                the royal entourage. He suggested that if U.S. helped <placeName
                    corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> by getting the <placeName
                    corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO">French</placeName> to pull back rather than fueling
                fires, <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> would work for a
                relaxation of tension in the area. He cautioned that, as with <placeName
                    corresp="rec8OcfTNjljldVnD">Namibia</placeName>, it would be difficult to
                achieve progress. Without making any comment on this proposal, <persName
                    corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Secretary</persName> said U.S. policy toward <rs
                    type="compound-subject" corresp="recD8UEyBEWnzRQtf">Sahara dispute</rs> would
                remain one of neutrality.</p>
            <p>9. During exchange on the <placeName corresp="reczjRL3lZSWirtil">Horn</placeName>,
                    <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Secretary</persName> said U.S. could see
                no possible justification for <placeName corresp="recrGN6dqTH4MaGw0"
                    >Cuban</placeName> military involvement in <placeName
                    corresp="recN9Eiz6DYwp5D1W">Eritrea</placeName>, as the dispute is purely
                internal. Such involvement moreover would be inconsistent with <placeName
                    corresp="recrGN6dqTH4MaGw0">Cuban</placeName> pretensions of <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rectswnul2C5uzE9Y">non-alignment</rs>. In fact, U.S. already has told
                Cubans there is no justification for them to remain in <placeName
                    corresp="recTaHDu8DL4OjK8b">Ethiopia</placeName>. <pb facs="0193" n="172"
                    xml:id="pg_172"/> Focusing initially on <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3"
                    >Soviets</placeName>, <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt"
                    >Bouteflika</persName> said they already had been ejected from two Nilotic
                countries and that no superpower should want to see the other superpower feeling
                humiliated. Superpowers should regard each other within the context of global
                issues, and the U.S. should not force the <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3"
                    >Soviets</placeName>’ backs to the wall if U.S. wants a <rs type="event"
                    corresp="rec6OIA4luUvtBKNn">SALT</rs> agreement. Both U.S. and <gloss
                    target="#t_USSR_1">
                    <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">USSR</placeName>
                </gloss> should “close eyes to some things” in the search for equilibrium. He said
                that during his recent meetings in Havana <persName corresp="recDY3Qj3ewYuDRni"
                    >Castro</persName> had assured him <placeName corresp="recrGN6dqTH4MaGw0"
                    >Cuba</placeName> would not become militarily engaged in <placeName
                    corresp="recN9Eiz6DYwp5D1W">Eritrea</placeName>. The problem demanded a
                political solution, and <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName>
                said he had pressed this view on <persName corresp="rec97wetyoXAfBn07"
                    >Kosygin</persName> and <persName corresp="rec2pzR5IgvBboOwH"
                    >Mengistu</persName>, as well as on <persName corresp="recDY3Qj3ewYuDRni"
                    >Castro</persName>. Asked by <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">the
                    Secretary</persName> why 17,000 <placeName corresp="recrGN6dqTH4MaGw0"
                    >Cuban</placeName> troops remain in <placeName corresp="recTaHDu8DL4OjK8b"
                    >Ethiopia</placeName>, <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt"
                    >Bouteflika</persName> said the Ethiopians fear new trouble in the <placeName
                    corresp="recpBVCPAnKA7NIEl">Ogaden</placeName>, and that the <placeName
                    corresp="recnr5ergRnRaCpGd">Somalis</placeName> clearly do not regard that
                chapter as closed.</p>
            <p>10. <placeName corresp="recJAi0OpNdSuYev5">Middle East</placeName>: During discussion
                on this topic, <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName> was
                highly critical of <persName corresp="recIigdM8sR9uq1Ip">Sadat</persName> in
                exchange which repeated main themes of <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt"
                    >Bouteflika</persName>/<persName corresp="recwoY153LTKW4SoC">Saunders</persName>
                conversation described <gloss target="#t_reftel_1">reftel</gloss>, with <persName
                    corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Secretary</persName> identifying questions regarding
                future of West Bank currently under consideration by Israeli Cabinet at U.S.
                request. <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt">Bouteflika</persName> urged that
                    <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviets</placeName> be given more
                prominent role in peace process.</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">Vance</hi>
                    </persName>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
    </text>
